st Entorprise\nFor Sale Here\nTHE N ORTHWI'BT ENTERPRISE\nQRTLAND Tacoma WEEKLY NEWS\n2216 S. E. 37th\nMary M. Dunc-n, Editor\nNOTI C E\nIMPERATIVEU\nAll new. MUST reach the\nPortland Office of The\nNorthwest Enterprise BY\nFriday noon for current\nissue. M.M.D.\nWE CATER T 0 WHITE TRADE ONLY SIGNS\nINCURS WRATH 0F YWCA DIRECTORS\nr A Social Action resolution adopt\ned by the Board of Directors of\nthe Young Women's Christian As\nsociation at its February meet\ning, was endorsed by the member\nship meeting. Feb. 21.\nThe resolution is as follows:\n\"Whereas. there has been a no\nticeable increase in the posting\nof discriminatory signs in res\ntaurants and other public service\nestablishments and in refusal gen\nerally to serve other than 'w'hite\"\ntrade. and i\n\u201cWhoreus, various methods have\nbeen am-mpxed Io correct such\ndiscrimination, but without ap\npnrput success: now therefore\n\u201cBe It resolved, that we go on\nrecord denouncing all forms of\ndiscrimination by \u2018We cater to\nwhite trade only\u2019 signs. or by m\nlerence or practice and\n\u201cBe it further resolved that we\nrecommend that all persons de\nvoted to democratic principles in\nthis community refuse to patron-\nSEATTLEITES HONOR\nPORTLAND VISITORS\nMrs. Gertrude Askey and Mrs.\nJames Lee spent Friday through\nTuesday last week in Seattle,\nwhere they had a grand time. shar~\ning their stay with friends. Mrs.\nAskey was the house guest of\nthe Lonnie Shields; Mrs. Lee the\nguest of the Fred Browns. Many\ninvitations were extended this\npopular duo; however. time being\nan element. only allowed their\nacceptance ot\u2018 a few of the cour\ntesies. Among them: Mrs. Ruth\nHranch's gala cocktail party at\nwhich were those two popular Ta\ncomans. Mr. and Mrs. Tate, and\nSeattle's prominent Dr. and Mrs.\nClarence J. Allen. Mrs. Shields ar\nranged a drive. around Seattle's\nscenic lake shore. and across Lake\nWashington floating bridge; Mrs.\nCorinne. 'l\u2018aylor's Bar-B-Q crab\nluncheon at Crawford's Sea Food.\nwas truly delightful; likewise the\nJohn Folling's party. Carl McGee.\nnephew of Mrs. Fred Brown. hav\ning spent several weeks in the\nSound City and Portland. accom\npanied the ladies about as his vn\ncation waned\u2014as he made ready\nto depart for the Windy City. \u201c1'\"\nbe returning.\" he confided.\nSOCIALS\nMrs. Lettie M. Polk. formerly\nof Denver. Colo., making her home\nin Portland with her son-in-law\nand daughter, Mr. and Mrs. Ray\nmond Wilson. is on an extensive\nvariation trip which will include\nWashington. D. and several\nmid-western cities. Mrs. Polk will\nvisit both her sons, Harry and\nFrank.\nMr. and Mrs. Ralph Flowers\nis vacationing in Los Angeles; vls\nitiug Mr. and Mrs. Cheater Dixon,\nbrother-in-law and sister of Mrs.\nFlowers. The Dixons, formerly of\nPortland and Keyport. Wash. are\nenjoying their ranch home which\nthey purchased before they left\nPortland.\nCORRECTION\u2014It\u2019s the YMCA.\nUSO 6. N. 'l\u2018lllamook instead of\nYWCA. The building formerly the\nbranch YWCA ls being rented by\nthe \u201cYM\u201d from the \"YW\" for the\nUSO program.\nWe are glad to make the cor\nrection. The \"YM\" needs all the\ncredit it can get.\nCLUBS\nMembers of the O. M. E. Club\nheld their annual St. Patrlck tea\nSunday. March 17, at the home\nof Mr. and Mrs. Alex Cook In\nN.E. Rodney Ave. Green and yel\nlow predominated as a color\nscheme carried out in daffodils\nand uhamrocks. The ten. table was\nespecially attractive with the St.\nUNDER NEW MANAGEMENT\nDUNBAR HOTEL\nJAMES BRAGGS, Owner and Manager\n328 N.W. sth Br. 9375\nPAINTING AND DECORATING\nCARPENTER REPAIRING\n__ For Information Call\n2A.: 6916 1022 N. E. Hid\u2014ST.\u2014 MU. 7830\nWait for It! The Book of\nthe Year: \u201cThe Forgotten\nWoman,\u201d the Negro Woman?\nof the Twentieth Century. 1\nize establishments that practice\ndiscrimination.\u201d\nMr!\u00bb Joe I\u2018. Skenon. presidew\nor Board of Dh-evtors. said in\nletter this week to several hun\ndred members of the that.\n\u201cour action by the board and the\nmembership is in harmony with\nthe total policy of th? YWCA and\nprevious steps that we have\ntaken against discrimination. We\nurge the cooperation of ewry\nuwmber of the \\'\\\\\u2019(\u2018A. and of\nevery rlub member in the (1550'\nelation, in nominating this vicious\npractice. and in helping to imple\nment our fundamental belie-i in\nthe democratic way 01' life and in\nthe worth and dignity of human\npersonality,\"\nThis resolution originated in tho\nSocial Arllon (\u2018onlr ittoo ol' the\nFirst Congregational Church. From\nthere it was sent to the Portland\nCouncil of Churches. which also\nconcurred in this action.\nPatrick motit\u2018. Individual squares\nof white iced cake bore the sham\nrock ,aud open faced sandwich ml\nhered to the color scheme. Mrs.\nSusie Redd. general chairman, was\nassisted by Mrs. Ann Shepherd.\nReceiving were: Mrs. Margaret\nGriffin, club president; Mrs. Mul\u2014\ntie Lock. and Mrs. Cook. Pouring\ndurings the hours 1 to 6 were:\nMesdames Rose Nichols, ltobertn\nBlackburn, Blanche Brown, Dixiu\ni 490 Mott, Grace Parnell, A. E.\nThrough its series of Sunday\nnight programs. Bethel's Senior\nMissionary Society is contributing\nmuch in u spiritual and intellec\ntual way as Well as from attend\u2014\nnnce.\nSpeaker for its program March\nit), was Mrs. George Thomas who\ninspired her listeners as she tulk\u2018\ned on the subject \u201cMarching\nFeet\"\u2014~feet of missionaries be\nthey yellow, brown, red, black or\nwhite; feet which tread the high~\nways and by-wnys\u2014home and for\neign lands. \u201cWe criticize the\nchurch\u2014say it has made mis\ntakes;\u201c it\u2018 so it\u2018s because it is\ncomposed of imperfects like us\n\u201cwho hate and seek revenge;\nneither of which work to achieve\na better life.\"\nMrs. Dorothy Gray, pianist, and\nMrs. Martha Mullen, vocalist. ren\ndered musical numbers. Mrs. 139\u2018\nutrice Graven presided. Mrs. Mary\nAustin. president, offered re\u00ab\nmarks.\nBethel held its third quarterly\nmeeting Sunday, March 17, and\nquarterly conference on Monday,\nFeb. 18. Both were presided over\nby Presiding Elder L. F. Green,\nwhose messages A.M. and RM.\nwere greatly enjoyed. The con\nference was largely attended. with\nall departments represented. The\nclass system (15 classes and as\nmany leaders) is well under way.\nWomen of First A. M. E. Zion\nChurch is holding a fellowship\nmeeting Sunday. March 31, at 3\np. m. at Zion, 2007 Williams Ave.\nRev. (7. N. Austin will preach\nand Bethel's Missionary Society\nwlll furnish the program mun\nhers.\nSICK and SHUT-INS\u2014\nMrs. Ruth Reed in Emanuel\nHospital. Mr. A. A. Jones, allho\nremoved to his home. remains\nquite ill. Mrs. Ruby Maddox IS\nout after several days in with :1\nsevere cold.\nComing! Earl Hines\nMcElroy\u2019s Ball Room\nMonday, April Bth\nBoyd. Maud? Banks. S. Saunders\u2018\nW. L. Myers, and Janie\u00bb Lewis.\nIt was a grand succes\ufb02.\nC. HERBERT BROWN\nPhone EA\u201c 791 l\nCHURCHES\nEDITORIAL\nDuo or Hm mus! important rno\u2018\nspnnsihiliviws 01' e-Vc-ry vltlzpn of!\n\u2018lhv l'nilvd Stulvs is to rngister.i\nand llwn m vou-f\nIn Washington, the Importnnli\nPrimary Ec-lctlnn\u2014\u201chk'h is fol\nlowvd by the General ElN\u2018llon in\n\\'u\\'c-n|lu-r-\u2014l.~ Juno 4. lmpnrtant\nmumy. sum- and national offices\nwill lu- decided to a wrm extent.\nSomv candidates will lu- eliminat-\nHI. \"them will gird tlu-msvlves for\n\u00abluressful ram-s in the General\nEll-cum].\nIt citizens of Washington have\nchanged their addresses or names,\n'or did not\ufb01'otv in the last direct\nFLASH!\nThe: Oregon Federation of Col\nored Women's (\u2018lubs will sponsor\na benefit tea on Easter Sunday at\nllw sum-ions home of Mr. and\nMrs. \u201don Brown. 112 N. Hancock\nSr. hours 1 to 6. Mrs. Barbara\nSullivan ls program chuirman for\nIlw ton. and Mrs. Ruth Flowers ls\ngmwrul ohuirnmn,\nCOMING George M. Hauser.\nDirecmr of Congress of Ruin!\nEquality, wi|l speak in Portland\nApril 1, at Library Hall at 8 p. m.\nMr. Hauser's appearance here is\nsponsored by the FeHowehip of\nReconciliation, the (\u2018omminlon on\nRace Relanons and the Portland\nBranch N.A.A.C.P.\nComing! Earl Hines\nMcElroy\u2019s Ball Room\nMonday, April Bth\nDO YOU KNOW THAT\n'rinclu-rs :t rumor\u2014THAT it'sl\na big onem\u2019l\u2018llA'l\u2018 it's about wo\nmen the ().b\u2018.L\u2018.\\\\'. women \u00ab1\nTHAT it's about the clubhouse\nthey propose to buyuto establish,\nri\u2019l\u2018llAT they don\u2018t rare how fast\nand tar you carry this rumor\n'l\u2018llA\u2019l\u2018 pruveeds from their Easter\ntea will go to the clubhouse t'uud.\n\u2019l\u2018liAT Dorothy .\\lt-tiuire, a. na\ntive of Omaha, Neb., co-starring\nwith George Brent and Ethel Bar\nrymore in \"The Spiral Staircase\"\ncurrently at the Orpheum, is\nknown quite well by the editor of\nthis column a former Omahan)\n\u2014~\u2019l\u2018ilAT she saw Miss McGuire in\nseveral plays before she was on\nthe screen.\nTHAT it is said they put a. wo\nman\u2018s head on a silver dollar be\ncause money talks. THAT the\nfirst woman was named Eve be\ncause she put an end to Adam.\n'i\u2018ilAT politics is being studied\nand talked about more today than\never in its history\u2014THAT women\nare more interested in it than\ntiieii~\u00bb\u2019l\u2018llA\u2019l\u2018 a great demonstra\ntion lot-ally was the political\nt\u2018oruni last Wednesday at the Ben\nson Hotel-\u00abTHAT the 400 women\n,_ Democrats and Republicans\nheard women speakers on either\nside tell why they are Democrats\nwhy they are Republicans.\nTHAT the special privileged (Re\npublicans) slung ntud at the\nmasses, the common working peo~\nple (Democrats). THAT they\n(the masses) ducked the dirty\nmud-\u00abTllA'l\u2018 they came out. clean\n~ATHAT the lU-niinute debate on\nuniversay military training offer\ned many good points for and\nagainst\u2014'i\u2018iiA\u2019i\u2018 il we force mili\ntary training, other nations